<DOC><DOCNO> AP891027-0089 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-27-89 1045EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     10-27 0336</FIRST><SECOND>PM-South Korea,0347</SECOND><HEAD>Radical Students Burn U.S. Flags, Battle Police</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Radical students burning U.S. flags,carrying a mock coffin of the South Korean president and hurlingfirebombs battled riot police today in Seoul.   One group of 300 students hurled rocks and firebombs at policeafter a campus rally in front of Seoul National University. Policefired tear gas and dispersed the protesters in 90 minutes.   The other group, consisting of 700 students from a rival group,held a campus rally at Korea University almost simultaneously tolaunch what they called a stepped-up anti-government and anti-U.S.campaign.   No arrests or injuries were reported in the protests.   The protest at Korea University turned violent as students triedto march off campus. The students fought police near the school'smain gate, throwing rocks and firebombs. About 500 police hurledtear gas back over the school gate, which was locked by schoolauthorities.   ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!'' and ``Yankee go home!'' the studentsshouted.   The students brought a mock coffin of President Roh Taw-woo andtwo large U.S. flags to the gate and torched them. They cheered asthick smoke rose into the sky.   The students shouted slogans accusing the Roh government ofsuppression and demanded the release of a radical student arrestedfor making an illegal trip to communist North Korea in July.   ``Release Im Su-kyong, flower of unification!'' they shouted,raising clenched fists into the sky.   Ms. Im was charged with violating the country's tough nationalsecurity law by making an unauthorized trip to the North to attenda world youth festival there. She was arrested after returning homein August.   South Koreans are barred from visiting North Korea, an enemycountry, without government permission.   South and North Korea have been bitter enemies since theirpeninsula was divided in 1945. They fought the Korean War in1950-53.   Radicals say the 43,000 U.S. troops stationed in South Koreahamper reunification of the peninsula. They are a small but vocalminority on college campuses.</TEXT></DOC>